Renewing your Indian passport in Ireland?
Don’t stress about the photo part. 

Found the perfect solution at the Photo-ME Booth in Liffey Valley—quick, easy, and compliant with Indian passport + visa requirements. You can even retake your photo until you’re happy, and only pay at the end!

Bonus: They also do ID, Irish passport, and US/China visa photos. Check out the PhotoMe booths available in -
Liffey Valley Shopping Centre (County Dublin)
Square Tallaght Shopping Centre (County Dublin)
Stephen’s Green Shopping Centre (County Dublin)
Tesco Roselawn (County Dublin)
Tesco Ennis Shopping Centre (County Clare)
Arthur’s Quay Shopping Centre (County Limerick)
Tesco Crescent Shopping Centre (County Limerick)
Tesco Extra Wexford (County Wexford)

Highly recommend if you want it done right the first time.

Tag a friend who needs this!

The last seven days in Ireland…
I thought I’d be able to document every moment, post every day, and share a perfect countdown—but life had other plans. Between the packing, the goodbyes, the late-night thoughts, and the million little emotions—I just couldn’t keep up.

I’m feeling everything right now. Gratitude for the memories, love for the people I’ve met here, excitement for what’s ahead… but also sadness, anxiety, and a sense of closing a chapter I wasn’t ready to let go of just yet.

Ireland gave me so much more than I expected. And even though I didn’t get to share every day of this final week, I’ve felt it all deeply. One last week, one last look, and then… a whole new beginning.

I know all of this is out there—
People talk about colours, kindness, inclusion…
But I never truly felt how real it is
Until someone from my own family had to face it.

Living abroad, you see it clearly—
Kids absorb everything.
And if we don’t talk to them, guide them,
It comes out in dark and painful ways later.

It’s now my responsibility
To help my niece understand what’s okay and what’s not.
To make her aware—of kindness, of respect,
Of the truth that skin colour does not define worth.

I want her to accept her own skin,
To love it fiercely and unapologetically.
And more importantly—
To stand up. For herself. For others.
To never be “too nice” when someone crosses the line.

Because bullies don’t always show up with fists—
Sometimes they come dressed in smiles and subtle words.

This is infuriating.
This is important.
And this needs to be taught from a very young age.
Especially when you’re raising children away from home.

#talkaboutit #raisingawareness #kindness #SkinIsNotAShade #standupforyourself #desi #breakinggenerationalcycles #colour #brown

This is my family away from home.
The ones who’ve turned this foreign land into something that feels like home.

Yes, I’m lucky enough to say—I have family in Ireland.
They’ve been my support system through some of my toughest times, always showing up with love, warmth, and comfort when I needed it the most.

Over the years, I’ve built a beautiful bond with my niece too—one that brings so much joy and depth to my everyday life. Her little hugs, laughter, and just being around her have made this journey even more special.

If your family lives with you abroad, you know how much easier it makes things. You don’t feel as homesick, and you carry a little piece of home in your everyday moments.

Also, a big shoutout to @jaijaitvofficial —my niece absolutely loves their characters and stories!
She’s learnt so much from them, and it’s fascinating to see how engaged and curious she gets watching them.
Thank you, @jaijaitvofficial for sending over the kit—she’s obsessed with it and hasn’t stopped playing since!

I’m truly grateful for them—to be theirs, and for them to be mine.

#gratefulthankfulblessed #familyawayfromhome❤️ #irishlife #desiabroad #notalone #ireland #desi
